<!-- Section 4: Understanding the Problem -->
<section data-section="understanding-the-problem" class="proposal-section hidden">
  <div class="proposal-content">
    <h2 class="text-2xl lg:text-3xl font-bold text-[#1B2A4A] mb-6">4. Understanding the Problem</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      Cloud9&rsquo;s consultants map application integrations and dependencies as part of their client
      engagements. Today, this is done using SharePoint lists, manually drawn diagrams, and institutional
      knowledge. The problems with this approach:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2 text-[#2D2D2D]">
      <li>
        <strong>Diagrams go stale immediately.</strong> The moment a diagram is drawn, the landscape
        changes. There is no connection between the diagram and the source data.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Redrawing for different audiences wastes time.</strong> An executive wants a simplified
        view. An architect wants protocols and data contracts. A developer wants API details. Each
        audience requires a separate diagram, drawn from scratch.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No single source of truth travels with the engagement.</strong> Integration knowledge
        lives in the heads of individual consultants, in scattered SharePoint lists, and in static
        images that may or may not reflect reality.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Impact analysis is manual.</strong> Tracing the consequences of decommissioning an
        application requires a consultant to follow connections by hand across spreadsheets.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      The visualisation tool replaces manual diagramming with a <strong>living, interactive integration
      map</strong> that pulls directly from structured data, renders dynamically for different audiences,
      and persists across the lifecycle of a client engagement.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

