    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1B2A4A] mt-8 mb-4">5.2 Why Single-Tenant</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      The RFP specifies multi-tenant architecture with active-active deployment, zero-downtime scaling,
      and cryptographic tenant binding. These are the right targets for a mature SaaS platform at scale.
      For a product launching with a small number of initial clients, this level of infrastructure is
      over-specified and adds cost without delivering proportional value.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>We propose single-tenant deployment: one isolated instance per client.</strong>
    </p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
        <thead class="bg-[#1B2A4A] text-white">
          <tr>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-medium">Concern</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-medium">RFP Architecture (Multi-Tenant)</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-medium">Proposed Architecture (Single-Tenant)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="bg-white">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>Data isolation</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Row-level security in shared database</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Separate database per client &mdash; physical isolation</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>Security assurance</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Depends on correct RLS implementation</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Guaranteed by infrastructure</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-white">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>Auth complexity</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Multi-tenant Entra federation</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Single app registration per client</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>Failure blast radius</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">One bug can affect all clients</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">An issue in one deployment cannot affect another</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-white">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>Cost at 1&ndash;5 clients</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">~$1,200/month fixed</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">~$120&ndash;376/month (scales with clients)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>Client onboarding</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Add tenant record, send Entra consent link, configure SharePoint (~30 min)</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Provision infrastructure, deploy application, configure DNS per client (~2&ndash;4 hours)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-white">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>Migration path</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Already multi-tenant</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Migrate when client count justifies it (~18+)</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      Single-tenant onboarding is more involved than multi-tenant, but this is a managed progression
      &mdash; Cloud9 gains operational independence in stages, and multi-tenant simplification arrives
      when the economics justify it.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>The application is designed for multi-tenancy from day one.</strong> All tables include
      <strong>tenant_id</strong>. All queries are tenant-scoped. API middleware extracts tenant context
      from auth tokens. Configuration is externalised.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>The path to self-sufficiency is built into the roadmap:</strong>
    </p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
        <thead class="bg-[#1B2A4A] text-white">
          <tr>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-medium">Phase</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-medium">Client Count</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-medium">Onboarding Model</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-medium">Who Onboards</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="bg-white">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>MVP</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">1&ndash;5</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">BrightKeep provisions infrastructure and deploys per client as part of the engagement</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">BrightKeep</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>MLP</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">5&ndash;15</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Cloud9 Operations Dashboard provides a guided wizard for self-service provisioning, deployment, and configuration</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Cloud9</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-white">
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2"><strong>Scale</strong></td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">18+</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Multi-tenant migration eliminates per-client provisioning entirely. Onboarding becomes a database record and two client IT approvals (~30 min)</td>
            <td class="border border-gray-200 px-3 py-2">Cloud9</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      Each stage builds on the last. Cloud9 is never locked into BrightKeep for day-to-day operations
      &mdash; they gain independence progressively, and the multi-tenant migration happens when both
      cost and operational simplicity justify it, not before.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Customer impact of the migration:</strong> ~5 minutes of scheduled downtime per client.
      End users do nothing &mdash; the URL, login, and experience remain identical. See Appendix D
      for the detailed process.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Why single-tenant now is cheaper than building multi-tenant upfront:</strong>
      Multi-tenant architecture adds approximately 15&ndash;25 person-days to the MVP build
      ($21,000&ndash;$35,000 AUD) for shared infrastructure, tenant routing, connection pooling,
      and HA configuration that provides no value until 18+ clients. It also commits Cloud9 to
      ~$1,200/month in shared infrastructure costs from day one, regardless of how many clients are
      live. Single-tenant starts at ~$120/month and scales only with actual clients. Over the growth
      period to 18 clients, the cumulative infrastructure saving is approximately
      $10,000&ndash;$15,000. When migration becomes justified, the 15&ndash;22 day effort
      (~$21,000&ndash;$30,800) is funded by the revenue from 18 paying clients &mdash; not by upfront
      investment before the product has proven its market. The total cost of single-tenant now plus
      migration later is lower than multi-tenant upfront, and the financial risk is spread across a
      period where Cloud9 has revenue to support it.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1B2A4A] mt-8 mb-4">5.3 SharePoint Integration Model</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>SharePoint is the source of truth and stays that way.</strong> Cloud9 consultants and/or
      their clients build and maintain SharePoint lists for architectural &ldquo;truth&rdquo;. The tool
      reads from those lists. It never writes back.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>MVP:</strong> Daily automated sync + manual trigger. One-way, read-only.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>MLP:</strong> Check-out model. Users can create working copies (scenarios) to add planned
      applications, remove deprecated ones, or rearrange the landscape. Working copies live in the tool
      only &mdash; no write-back to SharePoint. This enables &ldquo;as-is vs to-be&rdquo; visualisation:
      the synced data is &ldquo;as-is,&rdquo; the working copy is &ldquo;to-be.&rdquo;
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      This eliminates the source-of-truth problem entirely. No bi-directional sync, no conflict
      resolution, no data ownership ambiguity.
    </p>

